post_text:
How to protect Yourself and Others:
There are a few simple things that everyone can do to help slow down the spread of COVID-19
-Stay at home when you are sick
-Know how it spreads
-Frequently wash your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds or use a hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol if soap and water are not readily available
-Do not touch your face, nose, or eyes with unwashed hands.
-Physical (social) distance (stay 6 feet away from individuals that are not living with you)
-Wear a cloth face covering when around others that do not live in your household (they are currently required in the state of Washington to be worn in any public setting
-Cover coughs and sneezes with a tissue or use the inside of your elbow if a tissue is not available
-Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces daily (this includes tables, doorknobs, light switches, counter tops, phones, keyboards, toilets, faucets, and sinks to name a few)

https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/prevention.html

post_text: Great News! USDA approved the waiver to allow the feeding of all children under the Summer Feeding Summer Program (SFSP) model yesterday. This means we will be allowed to feed all children ages 1-18 years -- no questions asked. Also, special needs adults up to the age of 21 are also allowed to pick up meals. If parents will be picking up their children's meals without the student being present, they will have to complete an attestation form.

post_text:
PHYSICAL/SOCIAL DISTANCING:

Social distancing, also called “physical distancing,” means keeping a safe space between yourself and other people who are not from your household.
To practice social or physical distancing
Stay at least 6 feet (about 2 arms’ length) from other people who are not from your household in both indoor and outdoor spaces.

Social distancing should be practiced in combination with other everyday preventive actions to reduce the spread of COVID-19 Including
-wearing cloth face coverings,
-Avoiding touching your face with unwashed hands,
-Frequently washing your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.

Resources:
English: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/social-distancing.html
Spanish: https://espanol.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/social-distancing.html

Due to COVID-19, WIAA sports have been postponed until the end of December. The WIAA is making every effort to get all of the sport seasons in, but the schedules will be reduced to 70%. The following sports will be offered during these time frames for this school year only:

Dec. 28-Feb. 28
Basketball
Wrestling
Boy's Swim

March 1-May 2
Football
Volleyball
Cross Country
Girl's Soccer
Girl's Swim

May 2-June 28
Tennis
Fastpitch
Track
Baseball
Golf
Boy's Soccer

The WIAA realizes that the last season will end after graduation and the last day of school.
All athletes will still be able to continue to compete regardless if you have graduated or if school is out.

There has been no decision on middle school sports yet. We will keep you posted.

Dear Families
Please be informed that the Pandemic EBT application deadline has been extended to September 11, 2020. Every active student in the Toppenish School District should qualify for the Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) benefit card. If you were incorrectly denied benefits, please call or email Nora Flores @ 509-865-8093 or nflores@toppenish.wednet.edu with the following information:

§ Student first and last name
§ Student birthdate
§ Name of the school the student was enrolled between March-June 2020
§ Parent name and contact number and
§ Language preferred for communication purposes

All preschool students who attended TSD From March-June 2020, can also qualify for the P-EBT card no matter their age.

Toppenish School District is an equal opportunity employer and provider.

Parents: Please take a few minutes to complete the Planning Assessment Survey: http://bit.ly/accessinternet

It is important that you complete the survey from home and not from work. If you do it from work, it will measure the Internet at work. By doing it from home, it will be a true assessment of your home Internet connection. They are working on a project to improve Internet access in the state of Washington. This will eventually/hopefully help our students and staff with Internet access from home.

post_text:
Families Get Help to Buy Groceries

Due to COVID-19 school closures, families may be eligible to get help with food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT Emergency School Meals Program or P-EBT. This benefit is for ALL children in Washington who receive free or reduced-price school meals regardless of if these families accessed meals during the emergency school closures. Find out more by clicking on the link below.

https://medium.com/@waOSPI/what-is-pandemic-ebt-a7a086fcaf94

Familias Obtengan Ayuda para Comprar Alimentos

Debido al cierre de escuelas por COVID-19, las familias pueden ser elegibles para recibir ayuda con los beneficios de alimentos. Estos beneficios alimenticios se denominan Programa de comidas escolares de emergencia EBT pandémico o P-EBT.

Este beneficio es para TODOS los niños en Washington que reciben comidas escolares gratuitas o de precio reducido, independientemente de si estas familias accedieron a las comidas durante el cierre de emergencia de la escuela. Descubre más en https://medium.com/@waOSPI/what-is-pandemic-ebt-a7a086fcaf94

post_text:
The Toppenish School District in response to the presidential press conference this afternoon has decided to shut down all school operations starting Wednesday, March 18th. Our district believes the health and safety of our students, families and staff are paramount with the current COVID-19 situation in our state. All of our district buildings will be closed to the public starting March 18th.

Our preliminary plan is that we will be shut down to students and staff from March 18th through March 27th. We will continue to honor our scheduled spring break from March 30-April 3rd. We will keep a close watch as the situation with COVID-19 progress and tentatively expect that our staff will be able to begin to implement our online learning platform starting April 6, 2020.

**TSI FLAG FOOTBALL TOURNAMENT**

This year in a effort to get everyone some play time in the tournament we will use the following format:

The field will be 20 yards long. Each team of 8 will be given the opportunity to score. After the team on offense scores or fails to score that team will then play defense. After the other team has had 4 chances, two new teams of 8 will come on the field. Each game in this format will be for 25 minutes with no time outs and no half time. In the event of a turnover, the ball will change teams.

The game details are listed in the image below.

post_text:
Toppenish Student Engineering Team is competing in the NASA ANGLeS 50 Challenge.
The Apollo Next Giant Leap Student (ANGLeS) Challenge is a national challenge celebrating the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 mission by giving students the chance to recreate the landing using drones and robots.
Each team will build a replica of the lunar module and use a remote-controlled drone to land it on an 8-by-10-foot map of the moon’s surface. Students will modify and program robots and drones to explore the lunar surface and bring back a rock sample. The students will use the drone to retrieve the team’s lunar module and bring it back to the starting line.
The competition will be Saturday, June 1st at Central Washington University.
Top teams will be invited to the state challenge in July at the University of Washington .
#Apollo50
#ApolloNextGiantLeap

Help us congratulate one of our students, Jannely Z. as her beautiful artwork is appearing for the second time in a nationally distributed calendar, and raising awareness about affordable housing needs. The annual poster contest is part of the Housing America campaign, which highlights the national need for decent, safe, affordable housing in sustainable communities.

Her artwork will be printed on to a Liberty water bottle which will be sold and all proceeds collected will be going towards a scholarship opportunity. If you are interested in purchasing a water bottle please contact Carlos Reyes at Ph. 509.453.3106 x 117.

Boys shirts and pants size 5-6, 7-8

post_text:
Dedicated Hearts
-Kelly Roper

Dedicated hearts like yours
Are not so easy to find.
It takes a special person to be
So generous and kind.
To care so much for your fellow man
Is a quality all too rare.
Yet you give of your time and talents,
For all in need to share.
So thank you for being a volunteer,
We're privileged to work with you.
We want you to know how appreciated you are,
Not just today, but the whole year through.

Celebrating our volunteers! Once again thank you all for your hard work & dedication to our school district. 😁

Maite Fajardo is an incredibly sweet Kinder student at Kirkwood Elementary School who's ready to graduate!

She's very enthusiastic about first grade and what she wants to be when she grows up.

"I want to be a lot of things. Work at a restaurant maybe like my Mom or a Teacher too…I don’t know yet. I also love to sing! I would love to be a singer one day!"

Congrats on your Kinder Graduation, Maite! Your positive attitude and energy will surely bring smiles to all of your new classmates and Teacher! 😃

Read more about her goals and her experience as a student at Kirkwood in our current newsletter! #WildcatWednesday

Congrats on your Kinder Graduation, Maite! Your positive attitude and energy will surely bring smiles to all of your new classmates and Teacher! 😃

Read more about her goals and her experience as a student at Kirkwood in our current newsletter! #WildcatWednesday

Roc Irwin is a Freshman at CATS Academy & an extraordinary craftsman.

With the support of his family and instructor Steve Robles, Roc is thinking about a future doing what he loves.

"Right now, I'm more focused on high school and graduating. But my construction teacher, Mr. Robles has inspired me to think about construction as a possible job. I'd like to know more about Central Washington University and visit. And maybe study construction there."

Your determination and creativity will take you far, Roc! Keep it up!

Read more about his goals and his experience as a student at CATS in our current newsletter! #WildcatWednesday
